---
import BaseLayout from "../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Myths vs. facts"
  description="Common misunderstandings about gambling and gambling harm, corrected with plain facts."
>
  <header class="page-header">
    <div class="container">
      <p class="page-header__eyebrow">
        <a href="/understand-gambling">← Understand gambling</a>
      </p>
      <h1>Myths vs. facts</h1>
      <p class="page-header__lead">
        Misunderstandings about gambling can keep people from getting help. Here
        are some common ones, corrected.
      </p>
    </div>
  </header>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="container prose">
      <h3>Myth: "It's only about losing money."</h3>
      <p>
        <strong>Fact:</strong> Money is one part. Gambling harm also reaches
        relationships, work or school, sleep, and mental health.
      </p>

      <h3>Myth: "You have to gamble every day to have a problem."</h3>
      <p>
        <strong>Fact:</strong> It is not about how often you gamble. It is about
        harm and losing control. Someone who gambles occasionally can still be
        harmed.
      </p>

      <h3>Myth: "It only happens to a certain kind of person."</h3>
      <p>
        <strong>Fact:</strong> Gambling harm can affect anyone — any age, income,
        background, or gender.
      </p>

      <h3>Myth: "If I keep playing, I'll win it back."</h3>
      <p>
        <strong>Fact:</strong> Each bet is independent — past losses do not make a
        win "due." Chasing losses usually deepens the harm. This belief is so
        common it has a name: the gambler's fallacy.
      </p>

      <h3>Myth: "Problem gambling isn't a real addiction."</h3>
      <p>
        <strong>Fact:</strong> Gambling disorder is a recognized behavioral health
        condition. It affects the brain's reward system much like substance
        addictions do.
      </p>

      <h3>Myth: "People with a gambling problem just need more willpower."</h3>
      <p>
        <strong>Fact:</strong> It is a health condition, not a character flaw.
        Treatment and support work, and recovery is possible.
      </p>


      <div class="sources">
        <h2>Learn more</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><a href="https://www.ncpgambling.org/">National Council on Problem Gambling</a></li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
